messages.text: Investigation: Day 2
The following is a transcript of an interview between Agent Falco and the Dixons, recorded June 21, 8:08 AM.
Thanks for meeting with me this morning. I know it‚Äôs not easy to keep going through this again, but any information you could provide would really help me in my investigation.
Can you please identify yourselves for the recording?
I‚Äôm Lynette Dixon, Libby‚Äôs mother.
Darrence Dixon, Libby‚Äôs father.
Anna Mae Dixon, Libby‚Äôs sister.
Okay, and how old are you, Anna Mae?
Nineteen.
Are you in school?
Yeah, at Cedar Creek Community College.
But I‚Äôm a commuter. I live with my parents.
Where‚Äôs your bedroom at your parent‚Äôs house?
It‚Äôs upstairs.
Next to Libby‚Äôs room?
Yeah, well, across from it.
You two must be pretty close.
Yeah.
Did Libby ever confide in you?
Like, about what?
About boys, her job, maybe anyone who was causing her some trouble‚Ä¶
You mean like Duke Simmons?
Who is Duke Simmons?
Libby‚Äôs ex-boyfriend.
Simmons, as in Sheriff Simmons?
Yes, Duke is Cecil‚Äôs son.
Libby was dating the sheriff‚Äôs son?
No ‚Äî they broke up.
When did that happen?
Like, a month ago, I guess.
So around mid-May?
Yeah, I think so.
Do you know why?
Libby said she couldn‚Äôt stay with him.
Did she say why?
She was scared of him.
My daughter went to the hospital because of what that boy did to her.
I thought Libby was hospitalized during a depressive episode.
Duke gave her a black eye.
But Libby told the doctors it was an accident, right?
She was afraid for her safety, for Pete‚Äôs sake.
She took too many sleeping pills‚Äî
They had to pump her stomach.
They kept her for two weeks.
This is why we asked for help. We don‚Äôt trust the Sheriff‚Äôs Office‚Äî
We don‚Äôt see eye to eye with Cecil Simmons.
Okay. Let‚Äôs make a timeline here.
When did Libby start dating Duke Simmons?
Last year ‚Äî he asked her to the Fourth of July picnic.
When did she get the black eye?
In March.
They had been dating for about nine months by then?
That‚Äôs right, detective.
Okay, so what happened after Libby got the black eye?
Less than a week later, she overdosed and went to the hospital.
Did Libby tell you that Duke gave her the black eye?
No, not exactly‚Ä¶but she told Anna Mae that Duke sent her obscene text messages.
What do you mean, ‚Äúobscene?‚Äù
He was calling her a slut and a whore and stuff.
Do you know why?
She said he saw her talking to some guy in her chemistry class.
He‚Äôs the jealous type ‚Äî very possessive.
He acted like such a gentleman around us. He had us all fooled.
So Libby entered treatment at the hospital for two weeks in March.
When was she released?
April 1st ‚Äî I remember it was April Fool‚Äôs Day.
Okay. What happened next?
We kept her out of school for a few more days, and then she went back.
She‚Äôs about to be a junior at Immaculate Heart.
Okay, so she returned to school in early April but she didn‚Äôt break up with Duke Simmons until mid-May.
Yes. She was too scared.
That‚Äôs a long time. Nobody reported the abuse?
She wouldn‚Äôt talk about it.
And Duke‚Äôs the Sheriff‚Äôs son.
Simmons would sweep the whole thing under the rug if we accused his boy of something like this.
Of course we wanted her to break things off with him, but we didn‚Äôt want to press her.
We didn‚Äôt know how much danger she was really in.
Do you think Duke Simmons is responsible for Libby‚Äôs disappearance?
We don‚Äôt know ‚Äî he could be, right?
Or a random pervert took her by force‚Äî
Why else would the dogs lose her scent on the road?
I don‚Äôt know. But abductions by strangers are actually pretty rare.
So you‚Äôre just like them, then, huh?
You‚Äôre saying Libby ran away. Case closed ‚Äî is that it?
Absolutely not, Mr. Dixon.
No one‚Äôs taking this kidnapping seriously.
I‚Äôm exploring every possibility, sir.
I‚Äôll look into Duke Simmons, I can assure you.
But the Sheriff‚Äôs Office will protect him. You have to‚Äî
I‚Äôll tread carefully. Unfortunately, I‚Äôve dealt with this sort of thing before.
Anna Mae, did you know about your sister‚Äôs fake ID?
No.
You‚Äôre nineteen ‚Äî did she ever ask you to buy her cigarettes?
No, she didn‚Äôt smoke.
Does she ever drink alcohol?
I don‚Äôt think so‚Ä¶
She‚Äôs a good girl. If she did run away‚Ä¶
She probably got the fake ID to hide from Duke Simmons.
Mrs. Dixon, you were the last one to see Libby.
Did she seem upset about anything?
I really don‚Äôt know.
I was in such a hurry to get the groceries before bridge that afternoon.
She‚Äôs been moody lately, but she swore she was taking her antidepressants like she‚Äôs supposed to.
You told Sheriff Simmons that Libby‚Äôs boss called you the day she disappeared?
Yes, Mr. Keating called around 6 o‚Äôclock.
And that‚Äôs when you went out looking for her?
I called some of her friends, but they hadn‚Äôt heard from her.
Darrence was at the church ‚Äî he came home to help me look.
And you stayed home, Anna Mae?
Yeah, in case Libby came back or tried to call the landline or something.
Then you found Libby‚Äôs vehicle on Route 12, Mrs. Dixon?
Darrence and I did, yes. The keys were still in the ignition and her tire was flat.
And you recovered her cell phone.
Yes.
Do you have any idea who Bronco is?
That‚Äôs who sent the text message, correct?
We don‚Äôt know.
I didn‚Äôt recognize his number.
Sheriff Simmons said it was traced to a burner phone‚Äî
All the previous texts to that number had been deleted on Libby‚Äôs phone.
Did Libby have access to the internet at home?
Could she have met someone online?
We monitor her internet use ‚Äî Darrence installed a tracker on her computer.
It shows us every keystroke she sends and receives.
It‚Äôs for her own safety.
She doesn‚Äôt use the computer much, so I haven‚Äôt checked it in a while.
And Darrence checks the girls‚Äô phones sometimes.
They aren‚Äôt allowed to have passwords under my roof.
There are too many predators out there.
Has Libby ever mentioned Bronco to you, Anna Mae?
No.
Anything about an online boyfriend?
No.
She didn‚Äôt get online much.
You last saw Libby the night before she disappeared, right?
Yeah.
Did she seem upset or preoccupied about anything?
I don‚Äôt know. I should‚Äôve asked her ‚Äî protected her.
It‚Äôs okay, Anna Mae.
You can help us now by telling us anything you know.
I think she said she was gonna talk to Duke about something.
But I don‚Äôt know if she did or not.
Do you know what she wanted to talk to him about?
She said he always came into Scoops while she was working.
She didn‚Äôt want him to bother her anymore.
So she went to confront him?
I don‚Äôt know if she did.
I think she wanted to, though.
Do any of you know why she might have been out on Route 12?
It‚Äôs nowhere near her work.
It‚Äôs nowhere near anything.
There‚Äôs nothing but trees and rest stops out where we found her car.
How did you know to look out there?
Well, we didn‚Äôt‚Äî
My friend Judy said she‚Äôd seen Libby‚Äôs car by Exit 66.
She asked if Libby was okay, so we drove to the exit.
That‚Äôs when we called 911.
Okay. I‚Äôm going to review all of the information. I‚Äôll follow up with you soon.
Please find our daughter, Miss Falco.
Thank you for helping us, detective.
You‚Äôre welcome. I‚Äôm here for Libby.
I‚Äôll be in touch soon.
The following is an audio call from Deputy Tex Decker to Agent Falco, placed June 21, 11:29 AM.
Falco.
Hi, Agent Falco. This is Deputy Tex Decker from the Cedar Creek Sheriff‚Äôs Office.
I‚Äôve got the GPS records for Libby Dixon‚Äôs cell phone that you requested.
Excellent, thank you. I‚Äôm at the station ‚Äî are you in the office?
No, I‚Äôm at the service provider. I just got the records. I‚Äôll bring them by for you‚Äî
But I did notice something you might wanna check out.
Okay.
It looks like Libby‚Äôs phone ‚Äúpinged‚Äù on the GPS at a seedy little joint called The Junction. It‚Äôs about a few miles east of Exit 66.
What do you mean, ‚Äúa seedy little joint?‚Äù
Uh, well, it‚Äôs a motel. The kind that, you know, charges by the hour.
I see.
It‚Äôs supposed to be for truckers and motorists ‚Äî a spot to take a rest from the road or whatever.
Uh-huh.
Yeah, it‚Äôs often used for more, uh, sexual purposes, if you get my drift.
Illegal ones.
I see. But there‚Äôs no evidence that Libby was prostituting herself, right?
So what the hell was she doing at that motel?
I don‚Äôt know ‚Äî a drug deal, maybe?
Maybe, but there‚Äôs no evidence to suggest she‚Äôs been using drugs.
She was hospitalized a few months ago ‚Äî I think the doctors would‚Äôve noticed if she were an addict.
Yeah, good point. But she could‚Äôve picked up the habit after she got out‚Äî
You know, to cope with her feelings.
It‚Äôs possible, but we shouldn‚Äôt make a mountain out of a molehill‚Äî
Maybe she went to the Junction to meet a boyfriend.
It‚Äôs possible.
Okay, head over to The Junction, if you don‚Äôt mind.
See if the desk clerk remembers Libby checking in the day she disappeared.
Yes, ma‚Äôam.
I‚Äôm gonna get Libby‚Äôs cell phone out of evidence and send it to my tech team in Nashville‚Äî
They can pull the deleted messages between Libby and Bronco from the phone‚Äôs memory.
Sounds like a plan. The texts would tell us if he‚Äôs her drug dealer, boyfriend, or whatever.
Exactly. Meet me at Exit 66 after you check out the motel‚Äî
I‚Äôd like to look over the disappearance site for myself.
Sure thing, boss.
Deputy?
Yeah?
I‚Äôm not your boss. But I appreciate your cooperation. See you soon.
Godspeed.
The following is an email exchange between Agent Falco and Director Philomena Todd.
The following is a text message conversation between Deputy Decker and Agent Falco, initiated June 21, 1:07 PM.
Hi, Agent Falco. I‚Äôm at The Junction and I‚Äôve just spoken to the desk clerk.
Great. What can you tell me?
She remembers seeing Libby ‚Äî recognized her photo right away and pulled the receipt for the room for me.
Libby paid cash to rent Room 201 for three hours.
They don‚Äôt require a credit card as a security deposit?
Joints like this don‚Äôt ‚Äî but they do check ID and take down a name.
And Libby‚Äôs name is on Room 201?
No, but Emily Baker‚Äôs is.
That‚Äôs the name on Libby‚Äôs fake ID.
Did you check out the room she rented?
I sure did.
But everything seems to be in order.
Do you still want me to meet you at Exit 66?
Yes. I just arrived at the site.
Okay. I‚Äôm heading over.
5 minutes later
What did the Dixons say Libby was wearing when she disappeared?
Jeans, a floral blouse, and brown sandals.
Did they say anything about jewelry?
I think they said she wore a fake diamond necklace and some kind of beaded bracelet‚Äî
But I‚Äôd have to check the file.
Why do you ask?
I found pink beads in the cracks of the pavement ‚Äî five of them have black letters on them.
Black letters?
I‚Äôll send you a photo.
Agent Falco sends Decker a photograph of small beads laid out on the pavement.
They spell out the name ‚ÄúLibby.‚Äù
Whoa.
Perhaps there was a struggle, after all.
